rutinizes dramatic shifts in housing, the growth of charter schools, and the enactment of Empowerment Zone legislation that promises upward mobility and empowerment while shutting out many longtime residents. Foregrounding privatization and consumption, she offers an innovative look at the marketing of Latino space. She emphasizes class among Latinos while touching on black-Latino and Mexican-Puerto Rican relations. Providing a unique multifaceted view of the place of Latinos in the changing urban landscape, Barrio Dreams is one of the most nuanced and original examinations of the complex social and economic forces shaping our cities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnterprise zonesxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aEnterprise zoneszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aGentrificationxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aGentrificationzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aHousing policyxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aHousing policyzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aLatin AmericansxHousingxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aLatin AmericansxHousingxUnited States. 0aLatin AmericansxHousingzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aLatin AmericansxHousingzUnited States. 0aPuerto RicansxHousingxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPuerto RicansxHousingzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrban developmentxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aUrban developmentzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aUrbanizationzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093772740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937727423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn